\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 PROJECT HANDOFF SUMMARY \'97 ASAP STUDIO WEBSITE REBUILD\
Goal: Rebuild the current ASAP Studio website as a premium, fully responsive, optimized WordPress template that matches the intended Figma design, fixes all current quality issues, preserves all important interactions, and is clean enough to replace the current implementation.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
1. CONTEXT\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
The current ASAP Studio WordPress site is already partially built, but the execution is not acceptable.\
\
Current problems:\
- It does not feel premium enough\
- The design execution looks too weak / too cheap\
- Scrolling effects are not polished enough\
- Responsiveness is off on multiple devices\
- Padding / spacing is inconsistent across breakpoints\
- Hover states are either weak, inconsistent, or not properly implemented\
- The client is unhappy with the result\
- The project has already been delayed too much\
- The previous implementation caused avoidable friction and lowered trust\
\
This is not a \'93small cleanup\'94 task.\
This is a proper rebuild and audit task.\
\
The agent has access to:\
- The current website / current implementation\
- The Figma / Figma MCP source\
- Existing instructions / commands / references tied to the project\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
2. PRIMARY OBJECTIVE\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Rebuild the ASAP Studio page/template properly for WordPress so it:\
\
- Feels premium and high-end\
- Matches the approved design intent from Figma\
- Preserves all relevant features and interactions\
- Fixes responsiveness issues on all major device widths\
- Fixes padding / spacing inconsistencies\
- Audits and rebuilds all hover states correctly\
- Improves scroll and motion behavior\
- Loads fast and remains maintainable\
- Can replace the existing WordPress implementation cleanly\
\
This is not about patching.\
This is about rebuilding the page so it is finally strong enough for client delivery.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
3. NON-NEGOTIABLE GOALS\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
The rebuilt page must:\
\
1. Match Figma design intent closely\
2. Preserve all relevant current content and features\
3. Improve perceived quality substantially\
4. Include all hover states, motion states, scroll behavior, and section interactions\
5. Be fully responsive across major screen sizes\
6. Fix spacing / padding issues across all breakpoints\
7. Be WordPress-compatible and easy to integrate\
8. Be performance-first\
9. Be visibly better than the current version in all critical areas\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
4. CRITICAL FIRST STEP \'97 FULL AUDIT BEFORE REBUILD\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Before starting the rebuild, perform a complete audit of the existing website and Figma.\
\
This audit must cover:\
\
A. Section Inventory\
- Identify every section on the current page\
- Identify the corresponding section in Figma\
- Confirm whether the current implementation matches intent or not\
\
B. Hover State Audit\
For every section/component, check:\
- Does it have a hover state?\
- What exactly changes on hover?\
- Background change?\
- Text color?\
- Border?\
- Shadow?\
- Scale?\
- Image zoom?\
- Icon movement?\
- Underline?\
- Cursor behavior?\
- CTA animation?\
- Overlay behavior?\
- Any missing or broken interaction?\
\
Document each hover state section by section before rebuilding.\
Do not assume.\
Check everything.\
\
C. Responsiveness Audit\
Check the current site on multiple device widths and identify:\
- Broken layouts\
- Bad spacing\
- Inconsistent padding\
- Misaligned sections\
- Typography scaling issues\
- Overflow issues\
- Cropping problems\
- Bad stacking behavior\
- Touch/hover fallback issues\
- Broken nav or CTA behavior\
- Gaps that are too large or too tight\
\
D. Motion / Scroll Audit\
Check:\
- Which sections currently animate\
- Which sections should animate based on Figma/design intent\
- Which animations feel weak\
- Which animations are missing\
- Which animations hurt performance\
- Which scroll effects need to be upgraded or rebuilt\
\
This full audit should happen before implementation begins.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
5. WHAT NEEDS TO BE IMPROVED\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
A. Visual Quality\
- Better spacing system\
- Better composition\
- Better hierarchy\
- Better typography rhythm\
- Better image presentation\
- Better transitions between sections\
- More intentional visual polish\
- More premium feel throughout\
\
B. Responsiveness\
- Fix all breakpoint issues\
- Ensure clean scaling across desktop, tablet, and mobile\
- Correct padding inconsistencies\
- Correct section spacing inconsistencies\
- Fix stacking behavior\
- Fix text width / line length issues\
- Fix image crop / framing issues\
- Ensure touch devices still feel polished\
\
C. Hover States / Interactions\
- Audit every hover state\
- Rebuild every missing or weak hover state\
- Ensure consistency in transition timing and interaction logic\
- Make buttons, cards, links, icons, and media elements feel intentional\
- Hover effects should be clean and premium, not random or overdone\
\
D. Motion / Scroll Experience\
- Improve scroll-linked polish\
- Improve reveal animations\
- Improve section transitions\
- Improve CTA interaction feedback\
- Ensure motion feels smooth and premium\
- Avoid bloated or gimmicky animation\
\
E. Technical Quality\
- Fast load\
- Lazy load\
- Optimized assets\
- Minimal unnecessary JS\
- Lean animation setup\
- Good HTML structure\
- Clean CSS architecture\
- Responsive and maintainable code\
- SEO-conscious markup where useful\
- Basic accessibility handled properly\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
6. RESPONSIVE REQUIREMENTS\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Responsiveness is a major part of this task, not a side detail.\
\
The rebuilt page must be checked and work properly on at least:\
\
- Large desktop\
- Standard desktop\
- Laptop\
- Tablet landscape\
- Tablet portrait\
- Large mobile\
- Standard mobile\
- Small mobile\
\
At each breakpoint, verify:\
- Section padding top/bottom\
- Horizontal padding\
- Grid behavior\
- Card stacking\
- Heading sizes\
- Paragraph widths\
- Button spacing\
- Navigation layout\
- Image aspect ratio / cropping\
- CTA placement\
- Footer spacing\
- No overflow or broken alignment\
\
Padding and spacing must feel intentional, not improvised.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
7. HOVER STATE REQUIREMENTS\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Every section and interactive element must be reviewed before rebuild.\
\
Check and document hover behavior for:\
- Navigation items\
- Buttons\
- CTA rows\
- Cards\
- Team items\
- Portfolio/project items\
- Image blocks\
- Icon blocks\
- Links\
- Footer items\
- Any custom interactive component\
\
For each, verify:\
- Default state\
- Hover state\
- Transition timing\
- Ease / feel\
- Whether it matches Figma or current logic\
- Whether it should stay, be improved, or be rebuilt\
\
Nothing should be left vague.\
The agent should know exactly what each interactive element does.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
8. DESIGN DIRECTION\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Use Figma as the main source of truth for:\
- Layout\
- Typography\
- Structure\
- Composition\
- Intended interaction style\
- Spacing intent\
- Motion design direction\
\
Use the current site as:\
- Content reference\
- Function inventory\
- Interaction inventory\
- Section inventory\
\
Do not blindly inherit weak implementation from the current site.\
If the current site feels flat, clunky, inconsistent, or cheap, improve it.\
\
Do not invent a random redesign either.\
The task is premium execution, not creative freelancing.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
9. FEATURES TO PRESERVE / REBUILD\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
Retain and rebuild all relevant elements, including:\
- All current content sections\
- Current CTA logic\
- Hover effects\
- Section interactions\
- Scroll-based behavior\
- Approved design add-ons\
- Figma-defined visual details\
- Any meaningful interactive behavior already present\
\
If something is badly implemented but clearly intended, rebuild it properly instead of deleting it.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
10. WORDPRESS REQUIREMENTS\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
The result must be suitable for WordPress integration.\
\
Important:\
- Template-friendly structure\
- No unnecessary dependency bloat\
- Easy to replace current page/template\
- Clean, readable code\
- Maintainable class naming and structure\
- Realistic future editing path for the team\
- Avoid brittle hacks\
\
If using a modular structure, keep it lean and integration-friendly.\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
11. PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS\
--------------------------------------------------\
\
The rebuilt page must be optimized properly.\
\
Required:\
- Lazy loading for images/media where appropriate\
- Proper image sizing\
- Compressed assets\
- Minimal render-blocking code\
- Lightweight animation logic\
- No bloated libraries unless absolutely necessary\
- Strong mobile performance\
- Smooth hover/scroll behavior\
- Fast first render\
- Clean DOM\
\
Not acceptable:\
- Laggy interactions\
- Heavy animation libraries for simple effects\
- Unoptimized images\
- Janky scroll effects\
- Effects that hurt mobile performance\
\
--------------------------------------------------\
